In conclusion - Less of a sports bar and more of a trendy hangout spot.</Text>< pictures>

<rate>4< /rate><text>The exhibits always appeal to my inner child. Whether it be something I can play with or just an interesting educational display, it's always fun walking around and seeing what appeals to me. I especially liked the Illuminated fog, Geysers, Giant mirror, Colored shadows, Slinky trampoline and Scott Weaver's Toothpick sculpture. The giant mirror kept us entertained for quite some time as it was super trippy walking around in front of it. Bobby L showed his skills with the slinky trampoline. When none of us could do it for longer than 5-10 seconds, Bobby made it go on forever. The toothpick sculpture is impressive as well. It took the artist 40 years to make it, but he recently added his face to the sculpture. It was frustrating for some to find, but I found the whole process amusing. You should drop by to see if you can find it.</text><Pictures>None</Pictures>< response>

< Text>
One of my favorite dive bars in San Francisco. Variety of options on draft. None taste fresh, but all are cheap. $3 Tecate and PBR. Fast service. Booth seating which can accommodate large groups. This place has never been dead when I've gone, but I've never had problems finding a seat. Pool tables. Cash only.</Text>

The office staff is professional, the front desk ladies are welcoming, and the office itself is clean and beautiful, but...
My last couple of visits there were very disappointing.
I came in there for a cleaning and checkup. Dr. Michaels was very nice. He told me that my teeth were good and that I did not need anything besides a regular cleaning which I was about to get. The hygienist, however, was rude. She was lecturing me on how to brush and floss as if I  was a ten-year-old and tried to set me up for a deep cleaning I did not need.
Next time I took my daughter there, again for cleaning and a consult. I knew that my daughter needed a filling and a crown. She saw a different doctor.  This time it was a young female; unfortunately,  I don't remember her name.  She said my daughter needed a crown instead of a filling, and an implant instead of a crown.  Her assistant was trying to scare us into buying what we did not need, again. She was telling my daughter, who was 18 at the time, horror stories about receding gums and crowns falling out. All that in an effort to upsell. I decided to get a second opinion,  and I am glad I did.
I really liked that office in the past. I have been taking my kids there for many years. But all their staff and doctors changed and their values and ethics are not the same any more. I will be looking for a different dentist.<//Text>

<date>1581105316723< /date><rate>5< /rate>< Text>
Okay so this is place is definitely in the top for me. Dentist are scary even if you take 100% great care of your teeth. I had a eating disorder growing up that had destroyed my 6 front teeth. They were becoming see through on the bottoms and you could see the dentin part receding. It affected  my talking to potential jobs and just made me become extremely introverted. I'm applying to nursing school in September and I knew if I didn't fix my teeth I wasn't going to cut it through classes and progressing in my career. So we took the plunge and went to dr. Michaels. He was extremely up front about everything. He was honest, took the time to answer questions and was very caring. The hygienist were amazing and the front desk ladies are very helpful. I made the appointment for 2 weeks later and saved my money.
Day of appointment: they put me in a calming room, were extremely caring and attentive and helped keep me calm through everything. I got all 6 front teeth caped. I had temporaries put on that no one could tell were fake. ( temporary teeth suck so bad but it's only temporary and it does get better) lived off mortrin and smoothies for a week. I had the dental hygienist Michelle that put them on and she took her time making sure my bite was perfect. Nothing worst than hitting teeth when you're numb.
Last appointment: go back in for my permanent set. My goodness my gums are killing me but they got the temporary out fast and once again Michelle took her time with me and made sure everything was perfect for me. She even offered to put on temporary glue so I could make sure if the color was right. ( I didn't; the color was perfect already)
So here's what you need to take from my experience
I paid $3259.00 for 6 front teeth to be capped. I have Dental insurance but this is considered cosmetic. The worst part is hearing the noise as they grind the teeth for placement ( you're numb it's just so loud) but as of now I feel like I can finally take my life back. I can finally accept that I've truly healed from my eating issues because this closed the book on having to see the reminders each time I would  smile before. I'm so happy to finally have some of my life back. You don't realize how much of your personality sits right in your smile.
100% would do it over again if given the chance.<//Text>

I am absolutely terrified of dentists and all and any dental work which is
unfortunate, as it has probably been the catalyst for a good deal of my teeth issues. After thorough inspection by Dr. Michel and his staff and being walked through what my xrays showed, I discovered I had to have some fairly intense work done: removal of implant, bone grafting due to bone loss and a bridge instead put in its place due also due to bone loss, not to mention dealing with an infected bone/jaw from it. < UserId.>
116685828838888389122<//UserId.>
<username>Tricia Spencer</username>< Time>
1550513794078</Time>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< text>
How do you give a 13-year-old van a new lease on life?  You go to Economy Paint & Collision.  Don't let the cramped quarters fool you.  They make every inch of space work for them.  They are friendly and helpful, and most importantly, they do great work.

Yes, there is some minor orange peel if the light hits this small spot or that small spot just right, but it takes a whole lot of money and a whole lot of effort to get a repaint job that doesn't do that.  That was a concern for me, but the orange peel is so minimal that it has no negative impact at all.

From repairing the dings to taking extra care with the edges, it's just a superb job.  And the best part is that the paint looks like the original factory paint.  They don't use "their own" paints, as some paint shops do.  They check the vehicle's paint factory code and unless you are choosing to change the color, you get a finished look that looks like the original.  That choice of quality, matching paint makes a great deal of difference in the outcome.

The prices are excellent, even though you understandably pay extra with a van, truck, or SUV.  After all, it's a big vehicle.

Check out the before and after photos of the hood, as well as the before roof (practically bald from sun oxidation), and the overall after of the whole van, including the beautifully restored roof.

9 repaired dings, and a full body paint, with 2 coats of paint and 2 coats of clear coat, all finished right on time.  Yep.  I am a happy customer, and I'm pretty sure that if the van could talk, you'd hear it whooping and a hollering in the driveway.<//text>

<Name>Jeong Ko</Name>< review>
I was attracted to Economy Paint and Collision due to their advertised low prices and photos on their homepage. I met with Dennis to obtain an estimate for my 2006 Ford Explorer after speaking to him over the phone. Dennis spent at least 10 minutes patiently explaining to me about the technical aspects of painting a vehicle. Upon my arrival, I obtained an estimate. I also enjoyed our conversation as we spoke about political matters related to the armed forces and POTUS‚Äô policies.  I felt Dennis was trustworthy, extremely knowledgeable and experienced.
Economy Paint and Collision is a family owned business. I later learned that his wife Ann and their son also participate in the family business. I requested my S.U.V. be painted the same colors maroon and beige with pearls. I had at least 25-30 chips in my paint that needed to be filled before the paint job. I enjoyed my conversations with Ann as we spoke about family matters and how she ran the shop giving young men opportunities to work and become skilled employees. Ann treated her employees like family members and she truly demonstrated her care for them.
When I picked up my vehicle it was a rainy day so I could not see the exceptional shine I was expecting from the paint job and the pearls I had requested add to my paint. The next day, I washed my vehicle on a sunny day and noticed the beautiful work. I noticed all the chips had been filled and the paint had an incredible shine.
I could not be happier with the professionalism, excellence, and attention to detail Economy Paint and Collision provided to me and my 2006 Ford Explorer.

-Jeong Ko< /review>

<Name>Jenna Ali<//Name>< time>
1348243893811</time>
< rating>
5</rating>
< Text>
This mom and pop shop does it right.

Once upon a time, my car looked shiny and new.  Then, one Halloween, some @(#*$*)( kids egged my car.  The clear coat peeled, and over the next couple of years, the damage spread and spread until my car looked like... Well, let's not talk about it.  It's embarrassing.

I'd heard so many horror stories about Earl Scheib and paint places of that ilk, but I'm broke, so a fancy paint job was simply not an option.  Plus, who wants to put a fancy paint job on a nearly ten year old Elantra?  Not me.

So the internet, in its infinite wisdom, led me to Economy Paint.  First off, let's just take a moment to acknowledge how awesome it is that this little middle-of-nowhere body shop realizes the importance of having an internet presence!  Before and after photos?  Yes, please.  Reviews?  YES, please.

By the time I drove my sad little blue car out to Riverside, I felt pretty confident it was in good hands.  My car was quoted $250 to prep, as there was EXTENSIVE sanding involved, and $195 for paint.

I dropped my car off on a Saturday afternoon, and was told they would TRY to have it done by close of business Wednesday.  I received a call Tuesday morning letting me know it was ready to go!  Compare that with reviews of Earl Scheib, etc., where people's cars seem to hang in limbo for weeks at a time!

I was nervous about the reveal.  People had told me, "You're NEVER going to be happy with a cheap aftermarket paint job..."  But I was prepared to chalk it up to "better than having no paint at all!"

I didn't recognize my car.  The paint job is excellent.  Little dents and dings that previously had a very demo-derby look to them are barely even visible with the new paint job (note: they did not fail to repair these, I never asked them to).  It seriously looks like a brand new car.  I'm so happy with it.

Great service, great results.  I couldn't be happier.  Economy Paint is the way to go.</Text>

<Rating>5< /Rating>< Text>
Love this place. Very cosmopolitan in its demographic. Police contact is minimal and non-intrusive. There is a local street gang; those that i believe are members have left me to mine without so much as a sideways glance.
Only complaint? Bathrooms locked for co-vid 19. There are a number of homeless in the area who have Buckingham for their bathroom needs. They've always been very respectful of me. I can't imagine why the municipality would withhold such a basic, and necessary function from a people with so few options.</Text>

<Review>Middle Eastern/Armenian food can be so hit or miss. It can be a challenge to get things just right, particularly when the joint is jumping and the patrons are getting restless. That said, Seasoning Alley does shawarma right, with just the right amount of seasoning (ha!) and wonderful side dishes.

I had a late lunch here on Saturday. The Chicken Shawarma plate was very nice, with delicious hummus and a nice salad to go along with the generous serving of chicken. I don't eat much rice, so the gracious and lovely hostess, Gohar, offered Mutabbal as an alternative. Absolutely delicious!

The Alley has two locations, which I totally understand. The good places in the LA area tend to spread their wings (eg: Guisados) and pop up in new places to put a smile on the faces of new diners!</Review>< username>
Debra Anderson</username>

The best restaurant in Santa Monica.  Family style dining with a beautifully crafted menu. The fried catfish is delicious and I order it every time.  The sashimi,  oysters,  and braised short ribs are must haves.  The curry lobster is perfectly seasoned and melts in your mouth.  Sides of vegetable fried rice and crispy spinach compliment any main dish. The staff is courteous and efficient. I've been going here for years and have never had a bad meal or leftovers. It's not cheap $$$$ but worth every penny.<//Review>

<Pictures>None</Pictures>< review>
Chinois is a long-standing favorite of my family. Many happy occasions have been spent in this beautiful restaurant. The food is nothing other than excellent.  The menu is comprehensive and covers vegetarian and meat lovers‚Äô choices. We ordered the special softshell crabs and various items on the menu that included tuna tataki, Szechuan pancakes,  seared Maine scallops, Shanghai lobster, whole sizzling catfish and the grilled Szechuan beef, for dessert we shared a variety of menu items.
We had the pleasure of being served by Lisa, who is an exceptional server.  She offered suggestions, plated the dinner and  carefully timed the meal, so that we could enjoy each dish one at a time.  From the moment we walked in we were greeted with great hospitality. We also had the pleasure of meeting the wonderful Bella Lantsman, who has been an integral part of the Wolfgang Puck organization, in particular Chinois, for many years. We look forward to many more happy occasions there.</review>

I‚Äôm kind of used to the sterile medical clinic environment. 1622137146996</Time>
< rating>
5</rating>
< review>
LOVE THIS PLACE! If you like juices they have a JUICE FLIGHT so you can try all the flavors and figure out what you like best. Some of my friends might comment this is a vegetarian restaurant but get the pizza! It's about the fantastic vibes this place has, and honestly the portions are large enough for me to share with someone else. My vegan Mom got the Black Bean Burger and it came with A LOT of potato wedges which were delicious. I got the breakfast burrito, but I honestly would recommend something else because it was pretty basic, but large portions.
They have postcards that they can mail out for you, you just have to ask for it. If you're bent on coming here make a reservation because it looks busy every time I pass by. We were able to walk up on the weekday no problem though. The bar here looks huge too.
I would definitely recommend for a light bite and great atmosphere.< /review>

<name>Caspar Norris</name>< Review>
A little pricey but delicious food. If you‚Äôre vegan make sure you pay attention to the menu as it is a vegetarian restaurant by default for the most part. Reservations are recommended. Cute spots out side and inside.

I had the mushroom calamari, coffee, BLT and Farmer in Heels with no mayo and vegan mozzarella. Soy bacon was delicious. Mushroom calamari is a MUST. Farmer in Heels was good but I‚Äôm glad it comes in a small cocktail glass. The amount of basil makes it a hard drink to have more than 6oz of.

It‚Äôs Venice so parking is mostly a nightmare. On the backside of Abbot Kinney Blvd there is free parking lots, just gotta find a spot.< /Review>

< Text>
Everything is all vegetarian here..
so delicious ‚ò∫Ô∏è‚ú®
The egg avo and soyrizo omelet was alright, I felt like it needed some tang or spice. Maybe some bell peppers. The sauce they gave me was too spicy for me.

The poppy seed waffle was tasty! Nice and thick, Crispy on the outside, soft and fluffy on the inside. With some creamy cream on top. This was not too sweet, it was just right. More fruit plzzzz :D

The breakfast sandwich was a bit dry.  I took a bite and it scratched the back of my throat since it‚Äôs so dry.
Definitely needs some jelly or some secret special sauce. I enjoyed it nonetheless.

<Review>I don‚Äôt frequent vegetarian restaurants, but The Butcher‚Äôs Daughter has managed to get my attention for all the right reasons and has lassoed me twice. Above all, it has seriously good food prepared and served by a staff that is friendly and welcoming. In addition, its Venice location and ambiance are quintessentially L.A. which makes the experience all the more enjoyable, especially for us Angelinos who live here by choice and not necessity.

My most recent visit was on Friday, March 12, 2021, which by coincidence was a cold, drizzling day that was freezing by Southern California standards.  Due to the coronavirus, only outdoor seating was available, but fortunately the establishment provided propane patio heaters which made the overall experience pleasant until it was time to leave and face the elements once again. Speaking of the coronavirus and its role in our lives as the ‚Äúnew normal,‚Äù it was obvious that The Butcher‚Äôs Daughter takes the issue seriously by putting house rules in place to ensure the safety of its guests and staff. Many of its rules aren‚Äôt rules as much as they are courteous measures like offering single use menus and touchless payments to ease the worries of its patrons.  What was most impressive was that the staff was able to convey smiles hidden behind their masks through warm gestures of kindness and friendly small talk.  I felt that the staff genuinely cared about the quality of their products and  guest satisfaction.

On the last visit, my lunch date and I started by sharing the White Bean Hummus which would please even the most picky of hummus connoisseurs.  Served with grilled flatbread, the hummus is enhanced with grilled artichoke along with kalamata and castelvetrano olives making it impossible to eat slowly.  I hope I didn‚Äôt blow my chance for a second date by devouring more than my fair share of it.  For the main course, I had the Mixed Mushroom Pizza with a Golden Ale and my date had the Coconut Curry Bowl and a Spicy Mezcalita to drink.  Of course I only have good things to say about my pizza which was a thin crusted pie with a variety of mushrooms, hence the name, on mozzarella with garlic confit and white truffle oil.  Those ingredients by themselves are tasty, but when topped with arugula, the flavors bursted to life with a favorable impression.  The Golden Ale, made by Athletic Brewing Company, is by far one of the best non alcoholic beers on the market (I was the designated driver) and really added the final touch to my meal.  However, my date‚Äôs lunch, the Coconut Curry Bowl, was nothing less than sensational. He let me have a few spoonfuls of his curry although I‚Äôm sure he was probably taking precautions to make sure I didn‚Äôt eat it all like I practically did with the hummus. It was a rich combination of chickpeas, sweet potatoes, brussel sprouts, and French curry known as vadouvan.  Served with grilled flatbread, that curry was out of this world! Like I said, I enjoyed my pizza, but was definitely jealous of my date‚Äôs choice.  I didn‚Äôt try his Mezcalita, but he seemed to like it a great deal and I'm sure any mezcal lover would enjoy it as well.

The Butcher‚Äôs Daughter is so much more than a trendy, plant based restaurant.  It is a genuinely sweet and charming little eatery that could satisfy and please even the most aggressive of carnivorous appetites like mine.  Definitely a place you would visit more than once and a perfect spot to take out of town guests.  Absolutely wonderful!<//Review><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNJeQiG2gmADpw4TQ02HvjfNGkG25y42HsJc3kw=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOtqjmOnsFXZSeWNBpODrPz31V4CNuh2NoLwQYZ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics><response>None</response>< GmapID>

Excellent, bright setting for brunch. Adventurous cocktails and food. But high on the price. <user_name>Rick Lupert<//user_name><Response>None</Response>< Review>
Whoa is the butcher whose daughter launches a vegetarian restaurant‚Ä¶but for the rest of us vegetarians, we salute her branching out on her own path. We had a great experience at The Butcher‚Äôs Daughter restaurant in Venice. The restaurant had been on our radar for a while since we almost had brunch there a couple of months back, and decided to give it a try when the wait at another nearby restaurant was too long. We were seated right away on a Saturday night.

I started with a Rosemary‚Äôs Cup cocktail which was very refreshing and a tiny bit sweet with muddled cucumber and big pieces of fresh rosemary sticking out of it. Very well done.

My wife and I split the butternut squash risotto which was perfect as the split portions were large and the dish was rich so the full serving would have been too much for one of us. This dish had lots of flavor with a little bit of an Indian spice to it. This was a very nice take on butternut squash risotto.

We also shared the rainbow carrots ‚Äì A sweet dish full of multicolored carrots that would have been too sweet to eat on its own but perfect when shared.

I saw vegan sausage on the menu that normally comes as an add-on with the cheese board and asked if I could try that thinking it would be a good salty companion to the risotto. The flavor (white bean and fennel) was good although the texture wasn‚Äôt perfect for a faux meat.

We also got the Kale chips which was quite an experience top with a vegan parmesan Parmesan topped with lime. My wife was in love with this dish.

Although we didn‚Äôt order it, the veggie burger that walked by (okay, technically it was being carried by a human) looked amazing.

There were plenty of other things on the menu we didn‚Äôt get but would have loved to try, including desserts. We‚Äôll definitely be back.<//Review>

<user>100520055880557127012< /user><user_name>Justin Melbon</user_name><Date>1563965940772< /Date><rate>4< /rate>< review>
The Butcher's Daughter is a really nice place to enjoy brunch on one of the best streets in LA. I came with a few friends on Mother's Day and we were told that the wait was 1.5 hours, but it only ended up being 30 minutes so not sure how that happened but I'll take it.

The service was really good and was super attentive to our table. Checked in a good amount of times. I had a cold brew with a side of their rosemary simple syrup which was amazing. The syrup smelled like fresh rosemary so you can tell it was real rosemary that they used to make it. My friend and I split the surfers breakfast (breakfast burrito) and the buttermilk pancakes. Both were amazing, but the sizes are a littttttle small for the price. Only reason I'm not giving it a five star, but you can tell the quality was above average.

The place is also vegetarian so the name of the place is pretty comical if you think about it. Very clever. Interior aesthetic is super cute and they have a little patio section as well.</review>

<response>None< /response><UserId.>116753376728599569883<//UserId.>< Review>
The Butcher's Daughter is a really nice place to enjoy brunch on one of the best streets in LA. I came with a few friends on Mother's Day and we were told that the wait was 1.5 hours, but it only ended up being 30 minutes so not sure how that happened but I'll take it.

The service was really good and was super attentive to our table. Checked in a good amount of times. I had a cold brew with a side of their rosemary simple syrup which was amazing. The syrup smelled like fresh rosemary so you can tell it was real rosemary that they used to make it. My friend and I split the surfers breakfast (breakfast burrito) and the buttermilk pancakes. Both were amazing, but the sizes are a littttttle small for the price. Only reason I'm not giving it a five star, but you can tell the quality was above average.

The place is also vegetarian so the name of the place is pretty comical if you think about it. Very clever. Interior aesthetic is super cute and they have a little patio section as well.<//Review>

< Text>
Awesome experience! Believe the hype--it's pretty good, but be careful about the time you have. It took about 40 minutes to be seated but there's a variety of cute shops and stores around Venice to visit so the time flies. The service is great and every single waiter seems genuinely happy to be there and very helpful in general. I was pleased by the food and I'll probably be back one day. It's 30% for the aesthetic of the place, 30% the service, 40% for the food!</Text>

<gmapID>0x80c2bac74de94d6f:0x1e297f1177fa15df< /gmapID>< review>
The Butcher‚Äôs Daughter weaves itself seamlessly into the artisanally curated aesthetic that has become the predominant commercial style along Abbot Kinney Boulevard over the past 20 years. The restaurant‚Äôs vibe is distinctly upscale, but the rustic bohemian craftsmanship creates an open, inviting atmosphere that encourages clientele to hang out and enjoy the social experience of food, drinks and friends for which they came.

AESTHETIC - Rustic, Light & Vibrant

The 3,200 square foot space radiates with sunshine throughout the day. The entire area is bathed in natural light by 12-foot windows at either end of the restaurant, and - the key ingredient - the 20-foot ceiling that incorporates three pitched skylights among the exposed wooden bow truss beams.

Reminiscent of a well-worn white cotton towel blanketing a cream-colored sandy beach, the color palette chosen for the restaurant is a vital design element that combines with sunlight to create a comfortable, inviting mood. Primary features include a mix of exposed brick (painted white), white ash wood paneling, and tiles set in various shades of neutral. A myriad of secondary design elements - both structural and decorative - frame and give life to the baseline cream-colored palette. These include industrial aluminum light fixtures, visible brass piping, wooden three-blade Aviation ceiling fans, exposed structural steel columns, a variety of dangling green plants, a wooden bar and table tops, a steel hanging rack above the espresso bar adorned with plants and ropes, and artfully constructed, mirror-lined shelves installed behind the cocktail bar.

The open doors and windows at either end of the restaurant facilitate a fresh ocean breeze that flows through the space. This constant, gentle infusion of oxygen enlivens the atmosphere and promotes vibrancy.

PROGRAMMING - Creative & Versatile

That natural, bright space is programmed with six discrete settings:
+ sidewalk patio along Abbot Kinney
+ pastry display with to-go beverages and wine bottles for sale at the entrance
+ u-shaped espresso bar
+ traditional cocktail bar
+ indoor restaurant seating at a combination of booths, 2-tops, 4-tops and family-style share tables
+ outdoor back patio with a family style farm table

The spatial set-up provides customers an array of options to engage the space depending on the experience they seek. Sidewalk patio seating evokes a casual European cafe lifestyle. The entryway to the main dining room - with a to-go coffee bar, selection of pastries, and fully stocked refrigerator for any mood (fresh juice, beer, and wine) - provides patrons a quick in-and-out experience. There are two different bars that cater to distinct beverage inclinations: a traditional high-top bar features beer, wine and creative cocktails, while an intimate espresso bar inspires caffeine-infused consumption in closely-set wooden swivelling stools. Indoor seating throughout the restaurant accommodates any size party in search of a vibrant vibe. The picturesque backyard setting features a prominent wooden farm table and a tiled fireplace in the same motif as the interior. This space bursts with life, enveloping patrons in a variety of verdant hanging succulents, jade, fern, and bamboo, among other greenery.< /review>
</record>

<user>102449768374918139797<//user>< text>
The Butchers Daughter is a very Instagram-ready, aesthetically pleasing, Abbot Kinney ‚Äòmust visit‚Äô according to most reviews/foodies etc. It is very thoughtfully decorated and has a trendy vibe about it BUT...

As they don‚Äôt accept reservations there is often a long wait for seating, particularly on weekends, sometimes in excess of 1hr+. We were lucky to get bar seating for brunch on a Friday, unfortunately the swing around seats aren‚Äôt comfortable if you‚Äôre planning on having a good catch up with friends/plan on hanging out for awhile.

The service was good, with the hostess on the day being very friendly. There is however a mandatory 3% ‚Äúwellness tip‚Äù before the suggested tips which start at 20%. Absolutely no idea what the wellness tip is for? The service however was not exceptional or deserving of a minimum tip of 23%...I suppose this is an upside to working in an upscale eatery on AK.

The food was good but not as mind blowing as I was expecting. The price for both a pizza and a√ßai bowl were appropriate, particularly for the location. The a√ßai bowl could be a bit more creative. The prices of juices are a bit steep, particularly when the OJ was bitter and the size consists of about 3 gulps.

I‚Äôd try The Butchers Daughter again because they‚Äôre all vegetarian and have a wide range of vegan items and would recommend for those wishing to give it a go. But if you‚Äôre not overly phased and don‚Äôt want to wait for seating then there is better nearby! Overall, it felt like a lot of the people visiting were just doing it for Instagram likes.<//text>

109895799820959389827< /user_id>
<Name>Sung Han<//Name>< Time>
1570894144783<//Time>
< rating>
5<//rating>
< Review>
The interior is beautiful and had a lot of photo ops (if that's your thing). Despite the busy-ness of the morning rush- our order came out very quickly.

Avocado toast Benedict: Poached farm eggs, 9-grain toast, hollandaise & new potatoes.
From seeing pictures, we decided to go with this. Also... how can you ever go wrong with a Benedict? We were correct! Avocado is my absolute fav & with how fresh it seems to be here in Cali, it perfected this Benedict.

The best egg sandwich: Farm eggs, baby kale, avocado, cheddar & harissa mayo on a toasted classic croissant.
YUM. the harissa mayo with all the other ingredients on a soft but crisp croissant was so perfect to appease our hungry stomachs.

The juice flight (for a great price of $12 is a choice of 4 of their simple or heritage juices).
We tried the following:
- WATER FLOWER: Watermelon, Fennel, Honeydew, Lime & Lavender. Absolutely delicious! This one was my personal favorite. Not too sweet. Loved the flavor of watermelon and lavender.
- HONEY BEE: Grapefruit, Turmeric Root, Yuzu, Honey & Bee Pollen. This was my least favorite. I wasn't a fan of the turmeric and Yuzu.
- PURE PASSION: Passion Fruit, Jicama, Pineapple, Yuzu, Orange & Raspberries. Loved all the fruity flavors of this one.
- GODDESS OF GREEN: Kale, Cucumber, Apple, Fennel & Pineapple. This one tasted like a typical healthy vegan kale drink. The kale was def strong.< /Review>

< Text>
You'll have a love/hate relationship at this restaurant. There have been times when I've gotten good service here. During the weekends they'll get very busy and the regular wait times will be 30-45 minutes, on the plus side they will text you when your table is ready. There is an unlikely chance you'll get a good table. This restaurant will put famous people in priority first, they'll get served first, they'll get a table first, and they'll get the better table. Wherease there have been many times where they gave me and my friends the bar seating.

You go for the bougie pleasing aesthetic experience not the service. Its a nice place in a very crowded area. The food is very healthy and good (but expensive, just be prepared to spend money).

You'll want to park in the neighborhood behind the restaurant.< /Text>

<time>1510986614606<//time><Rating>5<//Rating>< review>
I thoroughly enjoyed this place. I've been to The Butcher's Son in Berkeley and was curious if this would be similar but it's totally different.

There is a mostly vegan menu that, even if you aren't vegan, you're guaranteed to love.

There is a great look inside of this place that feels like home with a positive vibe. It's fairly overpriced but every vegan place from here to Portland Oregon or anywhere else is like that. I wish this were different. But it's well worth the visit.<//review>

<name>Nicole Kohan< /name><Time>1531957313945</Time>< Rating>
4< /Rating>
<text>Cute spot for a veggie-lover's dinner. I enjoyed the decor and all of the little details and thought they put into the ambiance.

Service was on point! Hunter was super genuine and friendly. I'm not a fan of c communal seating; it's awkward when you have a large group and all want to sit together. Instead, the waitress opted to take us 7 girls back to a private table outside (the only table I saw on the back patio) which was super cute!! If you have a small party of 5+, this is the spot to be in. It had a glass fireplace to the side of us which was nice on a cool and windy night such as that one was, and a wall of real succulents behind us! I love succulents! The music was also quieter out there so we didn't have to yell to hear each other (too loud inside to catch up with girl friends).

DRINKS were very good! My friend and I had the Queen's tea or something it was called, and it tasted like a light alcoholic earl grey tea - so unique! My other friend had their special french wine which was also very good, I'm not sure of the name.

For FOOD, I shared the spicy Caesar salad and the burger (minus the guyreye cheese). We shared a regular margherita pizza as an appetizer. One of my girl friends had the "crab cakes" which she said were pretty good.  Overall I'd come here again.< /text>< Pics>
None< /Pics>

< review>
Never fails! Tonight we got the carbonara (which is made with spaghetti squash, egg, and cashew cheese), mushroom lasagna, and "crab" cake (made with quinoa and sweet potato). The carbonara was the surprise highlight of the evening!!!! The "crab" cake was incredible as well...
On previous occasions we had the cauliflower steak and cocktails; all magnificent!
Prices are standard for Venice ($$$), though some of the items were more reasonable than others.
The ambiance here is soo cute- like a rustic, cozy garden tastefully decorated, yet still very upscale.
We sat outside in the patio and it was perfect! Very romantic, every table was candlelit and the water comes with mint- nice touch :-)
Fantastic spot for a date!<//review>

<user_id>100658963178614735730< /user_id><Resp>None< /Resp>< Review>
I love the design and the concept of this restaurant.

Meal: I ordered the cauliflower TBone steak and it was just like the experience of eating a steak complete with charred edges, a steak knife, and a sauce that replicated juicy meat.

For a large vegetable, I felt like the price was a little high - almost the same cost as if I had ordered an actual piece of (beef) steak. There were no sides included in the price.

I would return again.</Review>

As the vegetarian daughter of a pig veterinarian father (you know, the person who keeps the pigs healthy for the butcher), I felt an immediate connection with this place (an exclusively vegetarian restaurant). My husband and I went on a Wednesday night and the place was full, but we got a table in under 10 minutes. Seating was a bit tight (I did get a accidental wack across the back of my head from someone trying to get to his seat), but not cramped. The service was good (friendly waiter, complimentary drink following drink order mishap). Food was great! My husband and I split the marinated olives (perfectly salty, warm, and oily), the impossible burger (same texture as a beef burger according to my husband), and the Carbonara ("angel hair" spaghetti squash). All were delicious, but the Carbonara could have used more salt (opinion influenced by Samin Nosrat's discussion of salt in her book Salt, Fat, Acid, Heat). Even so, the flavors were spot on (just needing some salty enhancement). Overall, great casual dining spot for vegetarians or anyone looking for more vegetable forward dinner options.<//text>

<review>This restaurant is trendy, overpriced, and unsatisfying to the stomach. I understand the need for updated trendy restaurants with interesting menu items. But I'm not one for trendy, I want staples. A friend was in town, and our other friend was closer to this restaurant and I wasn't asked for my opinions on a meal location. I had two soft boiled eggs and soldiers with jam. The soldiers (thick cut toast) were dry. The house made jam was unappealing. The eggs were made correctly and were good. My boyfriend and I had the same meal, he didn't touch his jam after one bite, I needed mine on the toast. It's a vegetarian restaurant, but I couldn't find much on the menu that even sounded appetizing to me. It was severely overpriced in our opinion.  I also got a ginger shot, which was nice and strong but didn't taste fresh. I shared a touch of it with my friend's vegan girlfriend, she was of a similar mindset. She had avocado toast with other stuff on it with a side of vegan sausage. The sausage smelled and looked delicious, but she didn't finish it so I can't be sure on taste. I wasn't interested in paying out the nose for an avocado on a piece of bread. That was my second menu choice if I hadn't gotten the eggs and soldiers.

If you enjoy the super trendy food cycle we seem to be going through and you have the funds to support your habit, you may enjoy this place. If you do not and are more of my persuasion, stick to your own kitchen.</review>< Name>
Kitty Love</Name>

<rating>2< /rating><Text>Loved it for lunch, so I took friends for dinner. The wait was 45 mins for a table for five - they do not take reservations - and half of the tables were empty for the entire duration of our wait.

I love the place and its concept - and I am known for loving to spend top dollar on extraordinary food. However, I found the prices for drinks at bar overly excessive - average wine $15/ glass - and my "Berliner Weisse" Beer was a disaster. Served from a can - aid you'd serve that in a Berlin beer place you are likely to get shot.

Then: dinner. Again, we love the place and the concept. Starters arrived only one minute before entrees. Our "Spaghetti Carbonara" - we know it's Squash Spaghetti - did not remotely resemble anything that compares to Carbonara. The waiter asked if we'd like it with bread crumbs - not that I ever heard that Carbonara is served with any bread in it - and we agreed. Sadly, it came without - and a check back why was ignored. To avoid any misunderstanding: it was nice - better was at $20.

Only two stars: we were constantly asked "may I take your plate" - even though the plates were half full. At one time, when engaged in a conversation with our friends, my wife did not respond quick enough - and half of her entree was gone. They did credit it on the check - but that was not the idea. She left hungry.

Finally, 20% gratuity was automatically added - they say customary for a party of five. For me: not good enough. I will not go again.< /Text>< Pictures>

Amazing vegan vegetarian... I had to come back and edit this review. I took my wife and daughter here because they are hardcore vegetarians borderline vegans but I fuel my machine in a state of ketosis. I only eat a ketogenic diet. I was forced to sit next to them while they ate the most incredible pizza that smelled absolutely divine they ate a salad that was to be honest ridiculously delicious looking and the juices that they had we're the best my daughter ever had. Several times people came up to me and said are you sure there's nothing we can get you like it was obvious that they felt bad that I was not able to eat anything from there. I made an offhand it mention that if I was going to cheat on my diet it would be to eat a piece of their coconut chocolate cake. When I was finished paying the bill and tipping one of the employees walked up to me and gave me a piece of cake for free with a smile and said here you go. They absolutely care here. I felt warmth and happiness. If you are vegetarian and you are looking for somewhere to go if you are a vegan and looking for somewhere to go this is not a place to be missed. Absolutely make sure you come here. By the way I said screw it and broke from my diet and I ate the cake and damnit that cake was delicious. Vegan yes but 100% delicious and full of flavor. If we find ourselves back in Venice we will most certainly be coming here.< /text>

<user>103916200039659142731</user><name>Lisa Blanchard<//name><time>1528565395794< /time><Rating>5<//Rating>< review>
So, so darling.  I kind of want to live in this space.  The white brick, the light wood, the cute farm stools, skylights, wood beam ceilings......it's what I visualize when I think of my perfect kitchen.

Full disclosure....I am not vegan.  I'm not vegetarian.  I don't need gluten free.  In fact, I kind of dislike vegetables.  However, I was with two of my favorite people who have embraced the LA lifestyle so when they suggested this place, I was game.

We came in solely for dessert and were NOT disappointed.  We ordered three different desserts and shared between us:  the warm ice cream sandwich (chocolate chip cookies with salted caramel ice cream), the apple crumb cake (with vanilla bean ice cream ala mode), and the raw pot de creme (chocolate mousse and chai bourbon).  ALL good!  We were in consensus that the apple crumb cake, which we didn't think would be our favorite, actually was.

The cookies with the warm ice cream sandwich would've been better if they had been warm but the ice cream helped to soften them and the caramel sauce drizzled on top was scrumptious.  The pot de creme was fairly salty.  I actually love salty and sweet together so it was good in that sense.  But the apple dessert was just perfection.  We really should've ordered three of those instead.

The service was friendly and efficient.  No complaints.

And the fact that they sell sage sticks to purify your space made me feel super LA.<//review>

<Date>1466207358474</Date>< Rate>
1<//Rate>
< Text>
Brought my 70 year old mum to this restaurant (that has celiac disease) as the restaurant advertises 'gluten free', and you assume a vegetarian restaurant would take care with customers with allergies...... So I sat through a tasteless lunch of bread and avocado for $15, but didn't complain as I was taking care of my mum.

However, as soon as we got home she started being sick and has now been throwing up for 30 mins.

Restaurants that don't take care of people with allergies are a disgrace, especially when they advertise the fact.

In London, an owner of a restaurant recently fed someone peanuts whom had nut allergies, and the customer then died.  The restaurant owner went to jail.  It's about time these restaurants took some responsibility.</Text>
